Question

A canoe travels 1.8 m/s relative to the water. A river, heading east, flows at 3.5 m/s. The canoe points at a direction 145 counterclockwise from east.


Find the canoes total speed, in m/s, and direction of travel, as degrees counterclockwise from east. (In other words, find the canoes velocity relative to the ground, in polar form.)

  • Speed = ##ANSWER1##
  • Direction = ##ANSWER2##

Answerlist

  • 1.9 m/s
  • 2.0 m/s
  • 2.1 m/s
  • 2.2 m/s
  • 2.3 m/s
  • 2.4 m/s
  • 22
  • 23
  • 24
  • 25
  • 26
  • 27

Solution

First, find the rectangular coordinates of each velocity vector. The two formulas:

\[x~=~r\cdot\cos(\theta)\] \[y~=~r\cdot\sin(\theta)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_1\) for the canoes velocity relative to water. It is shown below with approximate rectangular coordinates (found from formulas above, using \(r=1.8\) and \(\theta=145\)).

\[\vec{v}_1 = (-1.474,1.032)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_2\) for the rivers velocity vector. Since the river flows directly east, all of its speed is in the positive horizontal direction.

\[\vec{v}_2 = (3.500,0.000)\]

Now, add the corresponding components to find \(\vec{v}_3\), the velocity of the canoe relative to the ground.

\[\vec{v}_3 = (2.026,1.032)\]

Lastly, we need to find the polar coordinates. The formulas are given below. Notice, I am using the two-argument arctangent function.

\[r~=~\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\] \[\theta~=~\arctan(y,x)\]

So,

\[r=\sqrt{(2.026)^2+(1.032)^2}~=~2.273474\]

\[\theta=\arctan(1.032,2.026)~=~27.0085414\]

This can be visualized.



So, if we round like the answer choices, the speed of the canoe is 2.3 m/s at a direction of 27 counterclockwise from east.
